issue_body:
The sockets property sometimes returns sockets that have fileno < 0, which causes an error down the line. Since this doesn't happen all that often, I've not been able to debug the issue and its cause. I originally found the issue more than a year ago, so it's possible it has been patched since, but I didn't find anything relevant in the changelogs.

While I've successfully monkey-patched this in my client by only returning sockets with a non-negative fileno, the root cause obviously lies somewhere else (closed connections not getting cleaned up for some reason?).

My trivial patch for reference:
```python
def patch_client_reactor_sockets():
    sockets_orig = irc.client.Reactor.sockets
    @property
    def sockets_new(self):
        with self.mutex:
            return [
                    socket
                    for socket in sockets_orig.fget(self)
                    if socket.fileno() >= 0
            ]
    irc.client.Reactor.sockets = sockets_new
```

class Handler(BaseHandler):
    configuration = {'a' : 'b', 'c' : 'd'}

    @every(minutes=12 * 60)
    def on_start(self):
        self.configuration = {'a' : 'a', 'c' : 'c'}

    @config(age= 12 * 60 * 60)
    def index_page(self, response):
        print(self.configuration)

I changed configuration in on_start. But in index_page, it still print {'a' : 'b', 'c' : 'd'}.
How can I define a global variable?

I have a process running which continuously solves optimization problems with `solve_least_squares_lm`. I noticed that this process stalls seemingly at random with approximately with 12 hours in between (though this varies drastically).

This process runs on an embedded system so debugging is difficult but I managed to track down the culprit by inserting logging statements into dlib. Sometimes, the loop in [`dlib/optimization/optimization_trust_region.h`](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/ca498ac2d214fd679f8c641f90d08fb63cac11f6/dlib/optimization/optimization_trust_region.h#L273) runs indefinitely. The loop in question is

    while(stale_x || stop_strategy.should_continue_search(x, f_value, g))

I use a custom `stop_strategy` which limits the number of iterations to a predefined value (5 in my case). Apparently, this limit is not effectuated. I have a log statement as the first thing inside `should_continue_search`. When the stall occurs, I notice that `should_continue_search` isn't called anymore yet the operations inside the loop are still executed over and over. From that I infer that `stale_x` must be `true` and in turn short-circuiting the expression so that the `stop_strategy` isn't evaluated.

It is easy to track `stale_x` in the code. Inside the loop, it only occurs here

    if (rho > 0)
    {
        x = x + p;
        f_value = new_f_value;
        model.get_derivative_and_hessian(x,g,h);
        stale_x = false;
    }
    else
    {
        stale_x = true;
    }

So it must be that `0 >= rho` indefinitely when the loop never returns. `rho` is defined as

    const type rho = measured_improvement/std::abs(predicted_improvement);

Most likely, `0 >= measured_improvement` (though `predicted_improvement` could be really large as well). Apparently, the solver gets stuck (can't improve further `x` further) and this stalls the entire process.

To me it seems strange that we repeat the loop at all when `x` is stale. Why not simply

    if (0 >= rho)
    {
        break;
    }

and let go of `stale_x` completely? If no improvement could be made in this iteration, how could there be any improvement in the next (assuming that the subproblem solver is a pure function)?

