I come here with a problem regarding multi-level nested relationships. Consider the following code:

```
from marshmallow_jsonapi import Schema, fields


class Country(Schema):
    id = fields.String()
    name = fields.String()

    class Meta:
        type_ = 'country'


class Author(Schema):
    id = fields.String()
    first_name = fields.String()
    last_name = fields.String()
    country = fields.Relationship(schema=Country, type_='country')

    class Meta:
        type_ = 'author'


class Book(Schema):
    id = fields.String()
    title = fields.String()
    authors = fields.Relationship(schema=Author, many=True, type_='author')

    class Meta:
        type_ = 'book'


book_data = {
    'id': 'book-1',
    'title': 'Fifty Shades of Marshmallow',
    'authors': [
        {
            'id': '1',
            'first_name': 'Dorian',
            'last_name': 'Grey',
            'country': {
                'id': '1',
                'name': 'England'
            }
        }
    ]
}


dumped_book_data = Book(include_data=('authors', 'authors.country')).dump(book_data)
print(dumped_book_data.data)

```

When you run the above code, you'll receive the following (**and, I think, a very correct one**!) result:

```
{
  'data': {
    'type': 'book',
    'attributes': {
      'title': 'Fifty Shades of Marshmallow'
    },
    'relationships': {
      'authors': {
        'data': [
          {
            'type': 'author',
            'id': '1'
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    'id': 'book-1'
  },
  'included': [
    {
      'type': 'author',
      'relationships': {
        'country': {
          'data': {
            'type': 'country',
            'id': '1'
          }
        }
      },
      'attributes': {
        'first_name': 'Dorian',
        'last_name': 'Grey'
      },
      'id': '1'
    },
    {
      'type': 'country',
      'attributes': {
        'name': 'England'
      },
      'id': '1'
    }
  ]
}
```

This shows that Marshmallow-Jsonapi has no problems when serializing multiple-level relationships. 

However, **loading the dumped object** seems to lose some of the data on its way.


```
loaded_book_data1 = Book(include_data=('authors', 'authors.country')).load(dumped_book_data.data)
print(loaded_book_data1.data)

loaded_book_data2 = Book().load(dumped_book_data.data)
print(loaded_book_data2.data)
```

Both of these print statements will return the following object, where the author's country is represented as its ID (instead of having the whole object nested in the author):
```
{
  'title': 'Fifty Shades of Marshmallow',
